article.headline: LSU holds Alabama State to record-low 19 points
article.linkText: Gunter not impressed with No. 3 LSU's 61-19 victory
article.story:
BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- Setting several defensive records made
for an easy night on the scoreboard for Louisiana State (No. 3 ESPN/USA Today; No. 2 Associated Press), but the
65-19 victory over Alabama State on Saturday night didn't impress
coach Sue Gunter.

	   ''I thought we were very lethargic, and we didn't attack Alabama
State's zone,'' Gunter said. ''We didn't play well on the offensive
end.''

	   LSU set a school record for fewest points allowed. LSU beat Prairie View 68-26 on Dec. 22, 2001.

	   The seven field goals by Alabama State (1-5) are also an LSU
opponent's low, breaking the previous low of nine done by Nicholls
State in 1994.

	   Kisha James and Ayisha Smith scored 11 points apiece for LSU
(6-0), off to its best start since a 14-0 start in the 1996-97
season.

	   LSU got off to a sluggish start after Smith scored the game's
first points on a layup just eight seconds in. The 2-0 score held
until Alabama State scored on a 15-foot jumper by Shameka Jackson
to tie the game at 2 with 14:57 left in the first half.

	   The Lady Tigers took the lead for good 53 seconds later when
Roneeka Hodges hit a 3-pointer from the right wing to break a 2-2
tie.

	   LSU outscored the Hornets 13-2 over the final 6:06 of the fist
half, as KeKe Tardy drained a jumper and scored on a fastbreak
layup to give LSU a 25-10 halftime lead.

	   LSU shot only 37.9 percent (11-for-29) from the field in the
first half and missed six consecutive shots after Smith's layup to
open the game. Alabama State committed four shot clock violations
in the first half and made only four field goals, going scoreless
in the final 3:15.

	   ''I don't think I've ever been in a game when the shot clock
went off that many times,'' Gunter said. ''I shouldn't complain and
be glad that we won.''

	   LSU scored the first six points of the second half, with Seimone
Augustus' jumper giving the Lady Tigers a 31-10 lead with just more than 
two minutes gone.

	   Alabama State went scoreless for a 7:49 stretch in the second
half, during which time LSU had a 20-0 run and limited the Hornets
to just five shots.

	   James scored all 11 of her points during the run, which ended
with LSU ahead 56-15 with 5:43 remaining. Tardy finished with 10
points.

	   All 13 players who dressed for LSU played at least four minutes,
and nine of them scored.

	   Augustus, a freshman who entered the contest as LSU's leading
scorer with 18.4 points a game, was held to six points.

	   ''We didn't play LSU basketball in the first half, and somebody
will sneak up on us and beat us if we keep playing like we did,''
James said. ''We have to come out with more intensity and win the
first 10 minutes of the game.''

	   LSU's defense forced 22 turnovers, one shy of its season
average, with five of those coming on shot-clock violations.
